{{Use American English|date=April 2016}} {{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}} {{Infobox video game | title = Epistory - Typing Chronicles | image = | caption = Screenshot of gameplay | developer = [[Fishing Cactus]] | publisher = Plug In Digital | platforms = [[Linux]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]] | released = {{Start date|2016|03|30}} | genre = [[Action-adventure]], typing | modes = [[Single-player]] | director = | producer = | designer = David Bailly<ref name=presskit/> | programmer = Thibaut "Thibz" Hanson<ref name=presskit/> | artist = Benjamin "RYan" Lucas (3D) and Amandine Flahaut (2D)<ref name=presskit/> | writer = Joseph J Clark<ref name=presskit>{{cite web|url=http://fishingcactus.com/presskits/sheet.php?p=epistory|title=Fishing Cactus Presskit - Epistory - Typing Chronicles|publisher=}}</ref> | composer = }}
'''''Epistory - Typing Chronicles''''' is a 2016 [[action-adventure]], typing [[video game]] by Fishing Cactus. The game was released on [[Steam Early Access]] in September 2015 and was officially released on March 30, 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://killscreen.com/articles/cure-writers-block-in-the-origami-world-of-epistory/|title=Cure writer’s block in the origami world of Epistory|work=Kill Screen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/epistory-puts-your-combat-typing-skills-to-the-t-e-s-t-1767957423|title=Epistory Puts Your Combat Typing Skills To The T-E-S-T|author=Mike Fahey|publisher=Gawker Media|work=Kotaku}}</ref> for [[Linux]], [[Microsoft Windows]], and [[OS X]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/02/28/epistory-release-date/|title=Happy Ending! Epistory Riding Fox Out Of Early Access|work=Rock Paper Shotgun}}</ref> In the game, a young girl rides a fox with three tails. The game's story follows a writer's writing process, which unfolds like paper on-screen and is narrated from the perspective of the writer's internal thoughts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/the-keyboard-is-your-mightiest-weapon-in-epistory-1734457740|title=The Keyboard Is Your Mightiest Weapon In Epistory|author=Mike Fahey|publisher=Gawker Media|work=Kotaku}}</ref>
== Development == [[File:Fishing Cactus Studio.jpg|thumb|The full ''Fishing Cactus'' staff]] Part of the challenge in making Epistory was to "feel like a game and not just a typing application". To that end, the developers emphasised player choice in gameplay design decisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fishingcactus.com/index.php/2015/04/03/epistory-it-all-starts-with-good-intentions/|title=Fishing Cactus development blog » Blog Archive » Epistory: It all starts with (good) intentions|publisher=|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> The game was developed in [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fishingcactus.com/index.php/2015/04/16/lessons-learned-while-switching-to-unity/|title=Fishing Cactus development blog » Blog Archive » Epistory: Lessons learned while switching to Unity|publisher=|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> using the Tiled map editor.<ref name=handmadevsrandomized>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fishingcactus.com/index.php/2015/05/26/handmade-vs-randomized-level-design-in-epistory/|title=Fishing Cactus development blog » Blog Archive » Epistory: Handmade vs randomized level design in Epistory|publisher=|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> The use of Tiled made the ground tiles look artificial, so this was fixed using Shader Forge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fishingcactus.com/index.php/2015/10/12/breaking-the-cycle/|title=Fishing Cactus development blog » Blog Archive » Breaking the cycle|publisher=}}</ref> The EFJI keys were used to move the character through the world to encourage good use of the home keys.<ref>{{cite web|title=Epistory Retrospective - Looking back over the development of Epistory news|url=http://www.indiedb.com/games/epistory/news/once-upon-a-time|website=Indie DB|accessdate=14 October 2017|language=en|date=22 March 2017}}</ref> The art design was influenced by another game project that Fishing Cactus was working on, with a World War I theme. Because the frame story of Epistory is about a writer, it seemed like a natural choice to have a paper-themed world. Later, the decision was made to take it into 3D and incorporate [[papercraft]] and [[origami]] designs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fishingcactus.com/index.php/2015/05/11/epistory-paper-on-art-direction/|title=Fishing Cactus development blog » Blog Archive » Epistory: Paper on art direction|publisher=|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> Epistory used random methods to populate levels with trees, which were then manually checked and edited by the designers before being saved as the level.<ref name=handmadevsrandomized/>
Epistory was released on Steam Early Access on 30 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fishingcactus.com/index.php/2015/09/22/epistory-save-the-date/|title=Fishing Cactus development blog » Blog Archive » Epistory: SAVE THE DATE!|publisher=}}</ref> Mac and Linux editions of Epistory were released on Steam Early Access in October 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fishingcactus.com/index.php/2015/10/31/trick-or-treat-epistory-halloween-update/|title=Fishing Cactus development blog » Blog Archive » Trick or Treat! Epistory Halloween Update|publisher=}}</ref> Chapter Two was released in November 2015, and the price was increased to $12.99.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fishingcactus.com/index.php/2015/11/24/the-story-continues-epistory-chapter-two-now-available/|title=Fishing Cactus development blog » Blog Archive » The Story Continues – Epistory Chapter Two now available|publisher=}}</ref> Due to the popularity of the early access edition of the game, the deadline for release was pushed back to 2016 and more resources were devoted to the art design of the game, resulting in art assets that didn't match the earlier levels of the game. These were used in later levels to give the impression of the world becoming deeper as the player explores it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fishingcactus.com/index.php/2016/03/07/how-extra-budget-can-increase-your-visual-quality-and-put-you-into-troubles/|title=Fishing Cactus development blog » Blog Archive » How extra budget can increase your visual quality… and put you into troubles!|publisher=}}</ref> Epistory was available in English, French and German from the early access period, and Spanish was added later on.<ref>http://www.indiedb.com/games/epistory/news/finding-the-right-words</ref> Mod support was added in June 2016,<ref>http://www.indiedb.com/games/epistory/news/major-update18</ref> which allows players to change the words they typed in-game, add translations, and add support for different keyboard layouts.<ref>http://www.indiedb.com/games/epistory/news/on-your-mods</ref>
==Reception== [[File: Epistory03.jpg|thumb|Gameplay screenshot]] The game was nominated for the Indie of the Year Awards at IndieDB.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fishingcactus.com/index.php/2015/12/01/indie-of-the-year-2015/|title=Fishing Cactus development blog » Blog Archive » Indie of the Year 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Had an honorable mention in the 17th [[Independent Games Festival]]'s Excellence in Visual Art category.<ref>http://www.igf.com/2016winners.html</ref> The game received "generally favorable" reviews, according to video game [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/epistory---typing-chronicles|title=Epistory - Typing Chronicles|work=Metacritic}}</ref> Multiple reviewers wrote in praise of its typing mechanics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/03/31/epistory-typing-chronicles-review/|title=Epistory - Typing Chronicles Review - Rock, Paper, Shotgun|work=Rock Paper Shotgun}}</ref> Joshua Vanderwall, writing for the Escapist, described Epistory as a meditative experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/video-games/editorials/binging-indie/16975-Epistory-Origami-Art-Typing-Indie#&gid=gallery_6120&pid=1|title=Epistory Origami Art Typing Indie - Binging Indie - The Escapist|date=March 31, 2016|work=The Escapist}}</ref> The game is a finalist for Best 3D Visuals at the Unity Awards 2016.<ref>http://www.indiedb.com/games/epistory/news/unity-awards-2016</ref>
==Localization== The game has been localized to 8 languages besides English: French, German, Spanish, Polish, Portuguese-Brazil, Russian, Czech (trans. Jan Balek) and Japanese.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/398850/|title=Epistory: Typing Chronicles Steam Page|work=Kill Screen}}</ref> The localized versions have been in some cases marked as significantly more difficult, because all forementioned languages use alphabets with more characters than English, e.g. Spanish (29 without accents),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish_orthography|title=Spanish Orthography on Wikipedia|work=Kill Screen}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=April 2018}} Russian (33 letters),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russian_alphabet|title=Russian Orthography on Wikipedia|work=Kill Screen}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=April 2018}} Czech (41/42 letters).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Czech_orthography|title=Czech Orthography on Wikipedia|work=Kill Screen}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=April 2018}} Despite the higher difficulty the localized game is still accessible to younger audience.
