{{Infobox film | name = Eulis Atjih | image = Eulis Atjih p.74.jpg | image size = | border = | alt = | caption = Newspaper advertisement | director =[[G. Krugers]] | producer = | writer = [[Joehana]] | starring = {{plain list| *Arsad *Soekria }} | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = Java Film Co. | distributor = | released = {{Film date|1927|||Dutch East Indies|df=yes}} | runtime = | country = [[Dutch East Indies]] | language = | budget = | gross = }} '''''Eulis Atjih''''' is a 1927 film from the [[Dutch East Indies]] (modern-day Indonesia); it was the second feature film produced in the country, after ''[[Loetoeng Kasaroeng]]'' in 1926. The [[silent film]] follows the lives of a [[native Indonesian]] family sent into poverty by the husband's splurging. ''Eulis Atjih'' was a commercial success in the Indies, but failed in international markets.
==Premise== A [[native Indonesian]] man leaves his beautiful young wife Eulis Atjih and their child to lead a life of partying. She falls into poverty and, when he returns several years later, he is also poor.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Eulis Atjih}}
==Production== ''Eulis Atjih'' was produced by Java Film Co., which had made the first film in the Dutch East Indies, ''[[Loetoeng Kasaroeng]]'', in 1926. The earlier film had left Java Film Coy in a poor financial after it underperformed; as such, for ''Eulis Atjih'' the company had to find financial backers.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=72}} The film was directed by [[G. Krugers]]{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=97}} and based on the novel by [[Joehana]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=76}} The film featured [[native Indonesian]] actors, including Arsad and Soekria. It was a black and white, silent film.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Eulis Atjih}}
''Eulis Atjih'' was the second film to include native Indonesians in its cast, and the second feature film produced in the country.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=379}} The native role was emphasised in the film's promotion; a poster for a screening at the Orient Theatre in [[Surabaya]], for example, wrote that the film's native cast was equal to any American or European one.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=74}} Of note is the film's use of the word "Indonesia", which was not to be formalised as a preferred term for the archipelago until the [[Youth Pledge]] in 1928.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=72}}
==Themes== The Indonesian film historian [[Misbach Yusa Biran]] writes that the film educated Dutchmen through its depiction of native Indonesian rites, including funerals and marriage, as well as sent a message to native audiences that splurging would only result in poverty.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=73}}
==Release and reception== ''Eulis Atjih'' was released in 1927, being screened in [[Bandung]] in August and in Surabaya in September.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=72}} It was a critical and commercial success in the country, especially among the [[Chinese Indonesians|ethnic Chinese]] community; the newspaper ''Pewarta Soerabaja'' wrote that the actress who played Eulis was "beautiful when her life was carefree, but looked like a villager when she fell poor."{{efn|Original: "''Pembawa peranan 'Eulis Atjih' terlihat tjanti' saat masih hidoep senang dan air moekanja beroebah seperti orang desa sesoedah djatoeh miskin.''"}}{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=73}} In Surabaya, the film was accompanied by music from the ''[[keroncong]]'' group under Tuan Kayoon.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=73}}
For international release, the Java Film Co. and Krugers emphasised the [[ethnographic]] aspects of the film. It was shown in Singapore, but was a commercial failure.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=76}}
==See also== *[[List of films of the Dutch East Indies]]
